# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jack-quinn-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The **1909 major league baseball season** began on April 12, 1909.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 7, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and Detroit Tigers as regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the sixth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 7 on October 16.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The Pirates defeated the Tigers, four games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago Cubs from the 1908 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League, the Chicago Cubs had a record of 104–49 but finished 6+1⁄2 games behind the Pirates, setting a record for the most wins in an MLB regular season without reaching the postseason, which has only been equaled once, by the 1942 Brooklyn Dodgers, who had a record of 104–50.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The 1909 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 14 with all but the Pittsburgh Pirates and St.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the regular season on October 3, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season was on October 7.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 16.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] 23 tie games (13 in AL, 10 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 16 with the Pittsburgh Pirates defeating the Detroit Tigers in the 1909 World Series in seven games.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1909-major-league-baseball-season] The 1909 season saw two teams move to three new venues.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The **1912 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1912.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 6, with the New York Giants and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the ninth modern World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 8 on October 16.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Giants, four games to three (with one tie), capturing their second championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1903.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1911 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each league.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] During the season, *Harper's Weekly* conducted a detailed accounting of the expenses of major league clubs, reaching a figure of approximately $175,000 to $200,000.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Rustlers renamed as the Boston Braves.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day, April 11, featured all sixteen teams, only the second time every team has started their season on the same day (first being two years prior with the 1910 season).
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 6.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] 13 tie games (8 in AL, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 16 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the New York Giants in the 1912 World Series in seven games.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 season saw two teams play their last seasons at their respective venues.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] The 1912 season saw three teams play in new venues.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, was renamed to Robison Field by Helene Britton, named after her father and uncle, Frank and Stanley Robison, respectively.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1912-major-league-baseball-season] To accommodate for large crowds, the New York Highlanders would play three home games at the Brush Stadium, home of the New York Giants, on May 30 and a doubleheader on September 2.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The **1913 major league baseball season** began on April 9, 1913.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 5, with the New York Giants and Philadelphia Athletics as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the tenth World Series on October 7 and ended with Game 5 on October 11.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] In the third iteration of this World Series matchup, the Athletics defeated the Giants, four games to one, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1911.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Red Sox from the 1912 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] This was the third of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each league.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Trolley Dodgers shortened its name to the Brooklyn Dodgers and the New York Highlanders renamed as the New York Yankees.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The 1913 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 9 with a game between the Philadelphia Phillies and Brooklyn Dodgers, while American League Opening Day took place the following day, with all AL teams but the Chicago White Sox and Cleveland Naps, playing.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 5.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 7 and October 11.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The National League ruled that umpires could no longer scout for teams, as was the case when Umpire Cy Rigler was being paid $2,200 (equivalent to $71,700 in 2025) by the Philadelphia Phillies for his role in having the team sign a pitcher, Eppa Rixey.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] 21 tie games (5 in AL, 16 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 7 and ended on October 11 with the Philadelphia Athletics defeating the New York Giants in the 1913 World Series in five games.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The 1913 season saw two teams move to two venues.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox renamed White Sox Park to Comiskey Park, named after team owner Charles Comiskey.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1913-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves play two doubleheaders on April 19 and May 30 at the home of the Boston Red Sox at Fenway Park to accommodate large crowds.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The **1914 major league baseball season** began on April 13, 1914, with the first game of the inaugural major league season of the Federal League (having previously existed as a minor league the year before).
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The league declared itself as a "third major league", with its own eight teams, in competition with the established National and American Leagues.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League regular season ended on October 6 with the Boston Braves as champions, and the American League regular season concluded the next day with the Philadelphia Athletics as champions.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League season ended on October 10, and saw the Indianapolis Hoosiers winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason between the National and American Leagues began with Game 1 of the 11th World Series on October 9 and ended with Game 4 on October 13.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Braves swept the Athletics in four games, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Both the National and American Leagues rejected offers by the Federal League for a postseason matchup.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Philadelphia Athletics from the 1913 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This was the last of four seasons that the Chalmers Award, a precursor to the Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award (introduced in 1931), was given to a player in each of the established National and American Leagues.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers renamed as the Brooklyn Robins.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The major-league status of the Federal League was confirmed by the Special Baseball Records Committee (as convened by then-Commissioner of Baseball William Eckert) in 1969.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The 1914 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format first put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Most teams played more than 154 games, due to tie games (called on account of darkness or weather) that had to be replayed; tie games are excluded from team standings, but the statistics of individual players are included in their season totals.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 13, with a game between Buffalo and Baltimore.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, and featured all 16 teams of those leagues, only the third time those two leagues started their season on the same day (the 1912 season had been the second).
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National League had its final day of the regular season on October 6, while the American League's final day of the regular season was October 7.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series between AL and NL champions took place between October 9 and October 13.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 10.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] 43 tie games (18 in AL, 10 in NL, 15 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 9 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Braves sweeping the Philadelphia Athletics in the 1914 World Series in four games.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The National and American Leagues refused a postseason against the Federal League.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Across two leagues, Dave Davenport tied as a leader in saves at 6 (2 with the Cincinnati Reds of the NL and 4 with the St.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Attendance data for Federal League teams is unavailable.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] They previously played their on August 1 and August 8.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] In all, 29 of their 79 home games were played at Fenway Park.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1914-major-league-baseball-season] The team would only play at Fenway through July of the following season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The **1915 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1915.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League regular season ended on October 3, and saw the Chicago Whales winning the Federal League pennant.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season for the National League and American League ended on October 7, with the Philadelphia Phillies and Boston Red Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 12th World Series on October 8 and ended with Game 5 on October 13.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Phillies, four games to one, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1912.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Braves from the 1914 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series had again featured the cities of Boston and Philadelphia, though this time with their opposite-league counterparts.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Indianapolis Hoosiers relocated to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Buffeds, Chicago Federals, and Cleveland Naps renamed as the Buffalo Blues, Chicago Whales, and Cleveland Indians, respectively.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League brought an antitrust lawsuit against the National and American Leagues prior to the 1915 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The parties eventually reached a settlement and the Federal League disbanded after the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The 1915 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League, National League, and Federal League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place for the 1904 season, and which lasted until the 140-game schedule of 1919.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had its Opening Day on April 10, featuring all eight teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day for the American and National Leagues was on April 14, featuring the 16 teams of those two leagues, as had been scheduled the season prior.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Federal League had the final day of its regular season on October 3.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season for the National and American Leagues was October 7.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 8 and October 13.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The National League established that player-managers would count against the player limit, so the bench manager would be unable to insert himself in any game during the season without forfeiting the right to carry one of the players on his roster.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The penalty for violating the rule was forfeiture of the game.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] 31 tie games (10 in AL, 13 in NL, 8 in FL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 8 and ended on October 13 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Philadelphia Phillies in the 1915 World Series in five games.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Indianapolis Hoosiers from Indianapolis, Indiana to Newark, New Jersey as the Newark Peppers, they leave Federal League Park and move into Harrison Park.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Braves would play their last game at Fenway Park on July 26, having shared the park with the Boston Red Sox since the middle of 1914, and opened Braves Field on August 18, playing their final 26 of 78 home games and where they would go on to play for 38 seasons through 1952.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs would play their final game at West Side Park on October 3 against the St.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the home of the Chicago Whales (who would fold before the 1916 season), Weeghman Park for the start of the 1916 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] For games 3 and 4 of the World Series, the Boston Red Sox use the Boston Braves home of Braves Field due to its larger capacity over their home at Fenway Park (40,000 to 27,000).
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1915-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first year in a row where a World Series winning Red Sox used Braves Field.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The **1918 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1918.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended earlier than originally scheduled, September 2, because of a reduced schedule due to American participation in World War I.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The National League and American League champions were the Chicago Cubs and Boston Red Sox, respectively.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 15th World Series on September 5 and ended with Game 6 on September 11.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox defeated the Cubs, four games to two, capturing their fifth championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1916.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Chicago White Sox from the 1917 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 15 with four American League teams playing, the Philadelphia Athletics at Boston Red Sox, and the New York Yankees at Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day saw all eight teams play the following day.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] It was the first season since 1906 which saw the two leagues open on different days.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] With World War I ongoing, a "work or fight" mandate was issued by the government, requiring men with non-essential jobs to enlist or take war-related jobs by July 1, or else risk being drafted.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Baker granted an extension to MLB players through Labor Day, September 2.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] In early August, MLB clubs decided that the regular season would end at that time.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] As a result, the number of regular-season games that each team played varied—123 to 130 for AL teams and 124 to 131 for NL teams, including ties—reduced from their original 154-game schedules.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season would see all teams but the Cleveland Indians and St.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Later in August, Baker granted a further extension to allow for the World Series to be contested; it began on September 5 and ended on September 11.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] World War I would end two months later, with the Armistice of 11 November 1918.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] 10 tie games (6 in AL, 4 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 5 and ended on September 11 with the Boston Red Sox defeating the Chicago Cubs in the 1918 World Series in six games.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals is gradually referred to as Cardinal Field, after Helene Britton, daughter of the deceased former owner Frank Robison, sells her interest in the team following a deal in March 1917, ending the association between the Cardinals and the Robison family.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1918-major-league-baseball-season] By 1918, Cardinal Field became the name widely used.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The **1919 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1919.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Cincinnati Reds and Chicago White Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 16th World Series, known for the infamous Black Sox Scandal, on October 1 and ended with Game 8 on October 9.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds defeated the Chicago White Sox, five games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Boston Red Sox from the 1918 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The Black Sox Scandal, for which the 1919 season is best remembered for, saw the Chicago White Sox throw (purposely lose) the World Series to the Cincinnati Reds, 5–3, in order to illegally gain money from gambling.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This scandal resulted in the dissolution of the National Baseball Commission and the creation of the office of the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The new commissioner, Kenesaw Mountain Landis, banned eight players from baseball for life.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The 1919 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This 140-game schedule format had been previously used in 1903.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The 154-game schedule was re-instituted for the 1920 season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 19, when the Brooklyn Robins defeated the Boston Braves 5–2 at Braves Field in the first game of a doubleheader.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day (and most other National League teams' Opening Day) wouldn't take place until April 23, where each league saw six of their teams play.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the trend from the previous season which saw both leagues' Opening Day start on different days.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The National League regular season ended on September 28, while the American League regular season ended on September 29 with the New York Yankees defeating the Philadelphia Athletics 4–2 at Shibe Park.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1915 which saw both leagues end on different days, as well as the first season since 1903 that saw the leagues begin and conclude on different days.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series would begin in Cincinnati on October 1, before concluding on October 9.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The minor leagues withdrew from the National Agreement, resulting in the abolition of the Rule 5 draft, as well as all existing optional agreements between major- and minor-league teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The only way in which major-league clubs could acquire players from the minors was by directly purchasing their contracts.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] This change resulted in the previous $2,500 (equivalent to $46,400 in 2025) draft fee cap being removed.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (3 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/1919-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 9 with the Cincinnati Reds defeating the Chicago White Sox in the 1919 World Series in eight games.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Born in Štefurov, Austria-Hungary (modern-day Štefurov, Slovakia), Quinn emigrated to America as an infant with his parents Michael Pajkos and Maria Dzjiacsko, arriving in New York on June 18, 1884.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] His mother died near Hazleton, Pennsylvania, shortly after the family's arrival in the US, and Quinn's father moved the family to Buck Mountain, near Mahanoy City, Pennsylvania.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] In 1887 Quinn's father remarried, to Anastasia ("Noska") Tzar.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Quinn spent his early years working as a swimmer and blacksmith, while playing recreational ball for mining teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He got his start as a professional in an unusual way.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] While watching a semi-pro game in Connellsville, the 14-year-old Quinn threw a foul ball back from the stands to the catcher, hitting his mitt right in the middle.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] The visiting manager, from the nearby town of Dunbar, was impressed by the throw, and he offered Quinn a contract.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Quinn went on to spend 23 seasons in the major leagues with eight different teams.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He won 247 games and lost 218 games, also collecting 57 saves.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Quinn debuted on April 15, 1909, and he played until he was 50 years old; his final game was on July 7, 1933.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Quinn's professional longevity enabled him to achieve several age-related milestones.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He was the oldest Major League player to win a game until Jamie Moyer broke the record on April 17, 2012.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Quinn is also the oldest to lead his league in a major category (saves, in 1932—although saves were unknown in that era, and were only retroactively awarded in 1969).
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He is furthermore the oldest pitcher to start games in the World Series (with the Philadelphia Athletics, in 1929) and on Opening Day (with the Brooklyn Dodgers, in 1931).
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He was the oldest player to hit a home run in the majors, at age 46, until 47-year-old Julio Franco did so in 2006.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He remains the oldest Major League pitcher to hit a home run.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He was the oldest person to ever play for the Cincinnati Reds, and at the time of his retirement, the eight teams for which he had played also constituted a record, which has since been broken.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He was also the last major leaguer who had played in the 1900s decade to formally retire (not counting Charley O'Leary, who in 1934 made a comeback stint).
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Quinn is one of only 31 players in baseball history to date who have appeared in a Major League game in four decades.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He remains the oldest player to play regularly, having pitched 871⁄3 innings in 1932 at age 48 and 49, and 15 innings in 1933 at age 49 and 50.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] During his career, Quinn played alongside 31 different members of the Baseball Hall of Fame and collected two World Series rings in three tries.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He was also one of the last pitchers in baseball permitted to throw the spitball, grandfathered in along with sixteen others reliant on the pitch when it was banned in 1920.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He frequently used his spitball after he was grandfathered in, in addition to his fastball, curve, and changeup.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Quinn posted a .184 batting average (248-for-1349) with 90 runs, 38 doubles, eight home runs, 115 runs batted in and drawing 89 bases on balls.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] He recorded a .969 fielding percentage including playing several games in the outfield.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] Quinn died in Pottsville, Pennsylvania on April 17, 1946, three months after being diagnosed with a liver infection.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] His wife died on July 9, 1940 in Dolton, Illinois due to injuries related to a fall and necessary amputation of her right leg.
[src:jack-quinn-baseball/jack-quinn-baseball] In 2006, Jack Quinn was inducted posthumously into the National Polish-American Sports Hall of Fame.
